                        <handDesc>
                            <handNote xml:id="h1" script="Ethiopic">
                                <locus from="2r" to="15v"/>
                                <seg type="ink">Black, red</seg>
                                <date notBefore="1800" notAfter="1950">19th or 20th century</date>
                                <desc>Mediocre hand with angular script. Word dividers are also
                                    placed at the beginning of a line (e.g. <locus
                                        target="#5v #6r #10v"/>.</desc>
                                <seg type="rubrication">Initial two lines on the incipit page of
                                        <ref target="#ms_i1"/>; the first word of each stanza; the name
                                    of St Michael, erased names of individuals related
                                    to the production or ownership of the manuscript; elements of
                                    the punctuation marks, and numerals.</seg>
                            </handNote>
                        </handDesc>

                        <additions>
                            <list>

                                <item xml:id="e1">
                                    <desc>Scribal corrections appear interlineally (e.g. <locus
                                            target="#3v #4r #4v"/>) or over erasures comprising
                                        several words (e.g. <locus target="#12r #13v"/>).</desc>
                                </item>

                                <item xml:id="e2">
                                    <desc>Writing exercises and crude drawings on <locus from="1r"
                                            to="1v"/> and <locus from="15v" to="16v"/>; scribbles
                                        and doodles in the margins throughout the manuscript;
                                        erased notes in brown ink in the lower margin of <locus
                                            from="9r" to="11r"/>.</desc>
                                </item>

                                <item xml:id="e3">
                                    <desc> A white sticker with the name of <persName
                                            ref="PRS5782JuelJen"/> printed (<foreign xml:lang="gez"
                                            >ቤንት፡ ዩውል፡ የንሰን።</foreign>), and the signatures Ms.
                                        Aeth. g. 28 and Ms. Et 1 written in pencil is glued onto
                                        the inner side of the front board. Another sticker
                                        with the signature ‘Ms 1’ is glued below it. A note is
                                        written in pencil in the inner side of the front and back
                                        bord respectively with the shelf mark 'Ethiopian Ms 1' and
                                        the remarks 'Hymn to Yared' and 'Salutation to Mikael'.</desc>
                                    <!--<desc>to be checked: for correctnes and for completion of the note</desc>-->
                                </item>
                            </list>
                        </additions>

                        <!--
                                     <decoDesc> @Jacopo: Ornamental band in red and black with 'eyes' is drawn on the incipit page of <ref
                                target="#ms_i1"/>. </decoDesc>-->

                                <bindingDesc>
                                  <binding contemporary="true Ethiopian" xml:id="binding">
                                    <decoNote xml:id="b1">
                                      Bound in wooden boards.
                                    </decoNote>
                                    <decoNote xml:id="b2" type="bindingMaterial">
                                   <material key="wood"/>
                                </decoNote>
                                    <decoNote xml:id="b3" type="Boards">
                                      The boards are cut to the same size as the bookblock and have square edges.
                                      The grain runs vertically. The outer sides of the boards have a brown finishing,
                                      while the signs left by the working tool are visible on the inner sides.
                                    </decoNote>
                                    <decoNote xml:id="b6" type="SewingStations">2</decoNote>
                                    <decoNote xml:id="b7">
                                      The original sewing was a chainstitch on two sewing stations. It has been repaired with a different type of thread and
                                      in this occasion <locus target="#q3"/> has been re-sewn on four sewing stations. Nevertheless the sewing
                                      is still in a bad state of conservation.
                                    </decoNote>
                                    <decoNote xml:id="b9" type="Spine">
                                      The small holes close to the head and tail of the quires are probably what remains of quire tackets.
                                    </decoNote>
                                    <decoNote xml:id="b12" type="other">
                                      A red <term key="leafStringMark">leaf string marker</term> is attached to the upper outer prick of <locus
                                          target="#8"/>
                                    </decoNote>
                                  </binding>
                                </bindingDesc>

                                </physDesc>

                    <history>
                        <origin>
                            <origDate from="1800" to="1950" evidence="lettering"> </origDate> The
                            earliest date of production—taking into account the handwriting—can
                            be set to the nineteenth century. Several lines with names of
                            individuals who were probably related to the production or ownership of the
                            manuscript have been erased on <locus target="#15v"/>. It is not known how
                            and when the mansucript came into the possession of <persName
                                ref="PRS5782JuelJen"/>.</origin>
                    </history>

